      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0657P0-01489'>
        <a name='S5LV0657P0_20040113_GCR_55'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-david-filkin' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0657P0_20040113_GCR_55' title='Link to this speech by Mr David Filkin' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-david-filkin" title="Mr David Filkin">Lord Filkin</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            No, not so. I said that the state was entitled, as the Bill proposes, to have a process that allows for there to be a recognition in law that it is possible for a person's gender to be assigned and changed. The process is not a flippant one without evidence; it is not saying that the sunset is green rather than red. It depends on the tests set out in the Bill being met and tested by the panel. We believe them to be the right tests, and the appropriate tests, for so doing. Therefore, we believe that the state is absolutely right to legislate in this respect.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0657P0-01490'>
        <a name='S5LV0657P0_20040113_GCR_56'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-david-lytton-cobbold' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0657P0_20040113_GCR_56' title='Link to this speech by Mr David Lytton Cobbold' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
